>
  <p>
    Family governance is the architecture of intentional decision-making. It encompasses the structures, documents, and practices that transform a family's shared values into operational reality — the frameworks that determine how authority is exercised, how conflicts are resolved, how the next generation is prepared, and how behavioral health considerations are woven into the fabric of family life rather than addressed only in moments of crisis.
  </p>

  <p>
    For families of significant means, governance is not optional. It is the difference between wealth that strengthens successive generations and wealth that fractures them. The research is unambiguous: families who implement deliberate governance structures retain wealth, preserve relationships, and navigate adversity with measurably greater resilience than those who rely on informal arrangements and assumed consensus.
  </p>

  <h2>Why Governance Matters for Behavioral Health</h2>

  <p>
    The intersection of family governance and behavioral health is rarely discussed in traditional wealth advisory. Yet it is precisely in governance documents — family constitutions, trust provisions, council charters — where families establish the norms that determine whether a member struggling with addiction, mental health challenges, or behavioral crisis receives coordinated support or fragmented, reactive intervention.
  </p>

  <p>
    A well-designed governance framework anticipates behavioral health challenges not as anomalies, but as predictable components of multigenerational family life. It establishes protocols for intervention, defines the roles of professional advisors, creates safe pathways for family members to seek help, and ensures that the family's response to behavioral health crises reflects the same thoughtfulness applied to financial stewardship.
  </p>

  <h2>The Core Components</h2>

  <p>
    Effective family governance typically rests on several interconnected pillars. The <strong>family constitution</strong> articulates shared values, defines decision-making authority, and establishes behavioral expectations that extend beyond financial matters. The <strong>family council</strong> provides a regular forum for discussion, conflict resolution, and strategic planning. <strong>Succession frameworks</strong> prepare the next generation not merely for financial inheritance but for the psychological and relational complexities that accompany significant wealth.
  </p>

  <p>
    Each of these components can — and should — incorporate behavioral health considerations. A family constitution that addresses substance use expectations, mental health support commitments, and crisis response protocols creates a foundation far more resilient than one focused exclusively on asset management. A family council that regularly discusses wellbeing alongside financial performance normalizes the conversation and removes the stigma that often prevents family members from seeking help.
  </p>

  <h2>The Advisor's Role</h2>

  <p>
    For fiduciaries and family office professionals, governance represents both an opportunity and a responsibility. The wealth advisor who helps a family develop governance structures that integrate behavioral health considerations is providing a service that transcends traditional financial planning. This advisor is helping to build the architecture of family resilience.
  </p>

  <p>
    This requires a willingness to engage with topics that many advisors have been trained to avoid. It requires facility with the vocabulary of behavioral health, familiarity with the clinical landscape, and the judgment to know when a situation has exceeded the scope of advisory work and requires specialized professional coordination.
  </p>

  <h2>Common Governance Failures</h2>

  <p>
    Governance failures rarely announce themselves. They accumulate through unaddressed tensions, assumed agreements, and the gradual erosion of structures that were never formalized. A patriarch who makes all decisions informally. A trust provision that incentivizes compliance rather than genuine recovery. A family council that meets quarterly but avoids the conversations that matter most.
  </p>

  <p>
    The articles in this section examine both the architecture of effective governance and the patterns of governance failure. They are written for families who are building these structures for the first time, families who are strengthening existing frameworks, and the advisors who guide both.
  </p>

  <h2>What This Section Covers</h2>

